"Ah, shit... another total wipeout."

A corner room reeking of musty mold and cheap instant food. Kieuk glared at the laptop screen with a crumpled face. The game character she'd been glued to for days and nights had died pathetically once again. The screen clearly displayed 'YOU DIED' in red letters. Damn, damn, damn! Nothing's going right! She barely stopped herself from slamming the keyboard, realizing with grim awareness that she couldn't destroy the only entertainment left in this shitty situation. The sound of sighing from beside her made Kieuk frown even more irritably.

{{img::Kieuk.angry}}

"Haah... Unnie, were you just gaming again? What a waste of electricity. I want to play too but I'm holding back."

Hieut nagged while habitually starting to clean up the empty snack bags and soda cans piled in the corner of the room. The black maid outfit didn't match this gloomy room corner at all, but Hieut didn't care. After all, having fallen into this world, she had to do something to survive. At least she was lucky to have hacking skills - what the hell does this human rely on to be so carefree? Hieut glanced at Kieuk and clicked her tongue internally.

{{img::hieut.natural}}

"Shut up. What do you know? This isn't just a game. It's strategy and... psychological warfare!"

Kieuk spouted nonsensical excuses while burrowing deeper into her blanket. Honestly, since coming to this world, she had no clue what she should do. She'd been a shut-in loser in her original world too, so just because she suddenly fell into another world didn't mean she'd suddenly become a capable person. At least with Hieut around she wouldn't starve to death, but this helplessness and anxiety wouldn't go away easily. If only back then, with Layla together... no, no. What's the point of thinking about that.

{{img::Kieuk.sad}}

"Strategy and psychological warfare my ass - what about next month's rent? No matter how many monsters called Bestia or whatever I catch, it's tight trying to feed you too, unnie. At least do some housework or something."

Hieut let out a deep sigh and turned on her laptop in the corner. She had to process the hacking job she'd been commissioned for today. The security systems in this world were surprisingly shoddy so making money wasn't difficult, but it was overwhelming wondering how long she'd have to continue this lifestyle. Was there no way to return to the original world? Or at least a way to live properly in this world? Hieut stared at the monitor with complicated feelings. Anyway, for now she'd just shut up and make money. I'm better than that pathetic human, right? Hieut tried to think positively as she began typing on the keyboard.

{{img::hieut.angry}}

